<h3>Introduction</h3>

<b>Visual aids: "which ones belong together"</b>
<ul>
  <li> Vacuum tube, transistor, IC
  <li> Grocery calc, electronic calc, PDA
  <li> PCMCIA modem, desktop 2400 modem, acoustic coupler
</ul>

<h2>Abacuses, Looms, Arithmetic Engines</h2>

<h3>Early computers</h3>

<b>Messages: Commerce and military as drivers for high volume and
sophistication of mathematical operations</b>
<ul>
  <li> Dark ages to renaissance: invention of logarithms and
       mech. calculators
  <li> 50s-60s: large US companies using electronic computers
  <li> 1850's: Babbage, ballistic trajectory calculation
  <li> 1940's, ENIAC: same thing!
</ul>

<h3>Counting and Arithmetic</h3>
<b>Message:</b>  Replace hard operations (multiplication) with easy
ones.  Need to count preceded need to compute; the latter was the driver
for numeration systems, etc
<ul>
  <li> Abacus: 3000 BC.  It helps you count.
  <li> Zero invented in 650AD?  Orient? India? Mesopotamia?  Either way,
       it was really important: it allows radix notation, which helps
       you <i>compute</i>.  You need that for commerce and military.
  <li> Example with Napier's bones: (message: use addition only)
  <li> Radix based vs. symbolic numeration: do addition/mult. in Roman,
       decimal, binary,  for some driving app (e.g. tax forms)
  <li> Overview question: digital vs. analog.  What was abacus?  Slide rule?
</ul>

<h3>Babbage, Ada, the Difference Engine and the Analytical Engine</h3>
<b>Message:</b> It takes more than genius
<ul>
  <li> Example of the Difference Engine (message: use addition only)
  <li> Other inventions: sound actuarial tables; cowcatchers; various
       tools needed to build his engines;
  <li> operations research (<i>On the
       economy of machinery and manufactures</i>): industry benefits
       from scientific approach
  <li> Did Govt get its money's worth?  Machines never got built, and
       Babbage's ideas never fully appreciated till 1940's!  But,
       <i>we</i> got the benefits...is this a dilemma for Govt funding today?
  <li> Ada: saw the potential for the A.E. to do arbitrary data
       abstraction.  As far ahead of her time as Babbage was ahead of
       his.  But a lady of her time, societally!
       <ul>
         <li> Subroutines
         <li> Loops
         <li> Arbitrary data abstraction: representing things as numbers
       </ul>
</ul>

<b>Message:</b> Computation is about conditional operations and
programmed sequences.
<ul>
  <li>The evolution of calculation into computation; the Difference
       Engine vs. the Analytical Engine.  Conditional ops.
  <li> Jacquard's punch card loom
  <li> Ada: the inventor of programming!  (subroutine, conditional jump)
  <li> Ada: "We may say most aptly that the Analytical Engine weaves
       algebraic patterns just as the Jacquard loom weaves flowers and
       leaves."
  <li> Married William King, Earl of Lovelace; but continued
       intellectual relationship with Babbage and translated Menabrea's 1842
       Italian description based on Babbage's talk; added notes in which
       she basically described the concepts of programming: variables,
       conditionals, the subroutine.
  <li> Dark side of Ada: compulsive gambler, became mistress of a
       no-good, died of uterine cancer at 36.
  <li> Visitor to Babbage during dying years explained how he got a tour
       of Babbage's workshop, along with B's explanation of why he had
       never finished any of the projects.
  <li> B had said he would happily die early if he could come back 500
       yrs later for just three days.  What if he came back now?
</ul>

<b>Meanwhile back on the farm:</b>

<ul>
  <li>Silicon discovered in 1823 at Bell Labs??
  <li>George Boole's <i>A Logic?? for Representing Thought</i>, 1854
  <li> Lead-in to societal issues:
       An apparently intellectual process (arithmetic) can be performed
       by a machine!
       Could people of Pascal's time have foreseen the implications?
</ul>


<b>Visual aids</b>
<ul>
  <li> Slide rule
  <li> Grocery calc: descendant of early mech. calculators
  <li> Abacus
  <li> Sliding pebbles
  <li> Sign "Computer" to hang on a person
</ul>

<h3>Apotheosis of Mechanical Computers</h3>

<B>Computer evolution</b>

<ul>
  <li> Last discussion: digital vs. analog.  Today: Stored-program
       vs. fixed-program computers, and automatic vs. manual; and their
       lineage  
       through the Analytical Engine.   <i>What
       is a modern computer?</i>
  <li> Where did punch card idea come from?  Similar ideas used today?
       (scoring standardized tests)
  <li> Dates on timeline (intervals) get shorter as time goes on!  Why?
</ul>

<B>Hollerith and the census</b>
<ul>
  <li> Hollerith's relnship with census board deteriorated: they thought
       it was costing MORE when overhead considered! Do we have this
       problem today?
  <li> When was the last time census was assisted by mechanical (punch
       card) device?  1950!  (Univac-1 delivered in 1951)
  <li> Why is Zuse less remembered?  Hollerith had entrepreneurial
       vision, markets in mind (foreign govts., insurance co's, etc).
</ul>

