** 50s-60s, IBM and 7 dwarfs, early production computers,
transistorization, IC's, minis

   50s-mid 60s: "IBM and the 7 Dwarfs"; IBM 701; core memory (1951);
       transistorized Univac (1956); Univac I predicts election (1952 -
       get video!); FORTRAN compiler (1957); semiconductor IC Kilby at
       TI, Noyce at Fairchild (1958); Bell's modem  (1958)
** PEOPLE: Kilby, Noyce
** ANECDOTES: company mergers, etc; IBM strategy

** IC's enable minicomputers and supercomputers.  PDP-1, first commercial
       computer with mon & kbd (1960); PDP-8 1965;
       Multics 1965; Intel incorporated 1968; CDC 6600 and 7600,
       designed by S. Cray; Unix (Ritchie and Thompson) 1970; Xerox PARC
       est. 1970
** PEOPLE: Cray, Noyce/Moore, Ken Olsen

Moore's law: The economic efficiency with which IC's could be
produced, and the fact that the computers based on the new IC's could be
used to design their own successors, formed the basis of the observation
now known as <i>Moore's Law</i>: IC's double in performance and density
every eighteen months.  

