<h3>"A Computer on Every Desktop": Computing for the Masses</h3>

The IC made possible the first truly affordable <i>minicomputer</i>, Ken
Olsen's fabulously successful DEC PDP-8, and heralded the era of "garage
entrepreneurs" who would change the face of the industry.  Following a
bitter patent dispute, Bob Noyce and his associates would use the IC
concept to launch <a href="http://www.intel.com">Intel</a>, still the
world's most successful semiconductor manufacturer.

* Third wave: evolution from hobbyist to consumer: uprocs and PC's

** Uprocs: Intel 4004 Ted Hoff 1971; handheld calculators become wide
       spread; 1975 Altair 8800; 1976 Cray-1;

** MITS Altair 8800, MS Basic, Homebrew Club, 1976 Apple I, 1977 Apple
       foudned & Apple II; 1977 Microsoft; 1980 Osborne I; 1981 IBM PC;
       1982 the computer is Time's "man of the year"; 1983 Lisa, 1984
       Mac

** Apple II and Visicalc; the Killer App!
       


