@d225 14
a238 17
As computers became more powerful, people began to think of new ways of
using them, completely unlike the "number crunching" for which they were
originally intended.  Steve Russell, a graduate student at MIT,
demonstrated the archetype of all video games, Pong, in 1962.  Doug
Engelbart invented the mouse in 1964 at <a
href="http://parc.xerox.com">Xerox PARC</a>, just one year after
Ivan Sutherland had demonstrated Sketchpad, the first use of computer
graphics.  The proliferation of computer <i>programming languages</i>
used for these tasks (BASIC, FORTRAN and COBOL, to name three of the
most popular) caused people to realize that programming computers was as
substantial a discipline as building them.  The design of programming
languages, programs, <i>algorithms</i> for solving problems, and the
<i>data structures</i> on which they operated, quickly became a field in
its own right, based on the theoretical work of the genius Alan
Turing, which in turn traced its roots back to George Boole's work in
the 1850's.  In 1968, the NATO Science Committee Conference coined the term
<i>software engineering</i> and the new field was officially born.
d250 1
a250 5
<td>First reference to "Software Engineering" as a distinct discipline.
       First visionary glimpses of mouse-and-windows graphical interfaces
       (Engelbart, Sutherland), hypertext-linked content (Bush, 1952??),
       and games (Russell).

a252 9
<b>Quote:</b> "People don't realize that frivolity is the gateway to the
future, in that most future products don't start as necessities but as
toys." -Nolan Bushnell

<ul>
  <li> Vannevar Bush, <A
       HREF="http://www.isg.sfu.ca/~duchier/misc/vbush/">As We May
       Think</A>.  This 1945 article envisioned hypertext systems!
</ul>
