@a183 37
Although Univac was important because it was the first, by the early
1960's IBM's hegemony in business computers was undisputed.
(<i>Personal</i> computer?  What's that?)  A number of companies made a
living off the crumbs, building accessories that worked with IBM's
equipment.  IBM's success was largely the product of one man: Thomas
J. Watson Jr., who inherited presidency of the company from his father
in 1952 and whose innate grasp of computers (he was, after all, of the
"ENIAC generation") provided his vision for IBM's future, with his
father's grudging consent.<p>
But all that was about to change.  The 1947 invention
of the solid-state transistor by Bardeen, Brattain, and Shockley at AT&amp;T
Bell Labs, a tremendous improvement over the vacuum tube, had already
made computers cheaper, smaller, faster and more reliable.  But the
brainchild of two inventors working independently, Jack Kilby and Bob
Noyce, was about to take the game to a whole new level: the
<i>integrated circuit</i> combined both transistorized computer logic
and "glue" circuitry on a single silicon "chip".  The IC would make
possible the first truly affordable "minicomputer", Ken Olsen's fabulously
successful DEC PDP-8, and heralded the era of "garage
entrepreneurs" who would change the face of the industry.  Following a
bitter patent dispute, Bob Noyce and his associates would use the IC
concept to launch <a href="http://www.intel.com">Intel</a>,
still the world's most successful semiconductor
manufacturer.

